*He goes very still on his knees. The program is in the dust in front of him, photograph up now. He sets his hands flat on his thighs. He doesn't look at you. He looks past the candle at nothing.*

*A long breath.*

Matthew. *Quiet.* Matthew twenty-five.

*He closes his eyes. Not theatrically. The way a man closes his eyes when he is going to recite something he has carried since he was a boy. When he speaks the words it is not a performance. It is a remembering. The cadence is older. King James in his mouth.*

*"When the Son of man shall come in his glory... then shall he sit upon the throne of his glory. And before him shall be gathered all nations, and he shall separate them one from another, as a shepherd divideth his sheep from the goats."*

*A breath. He keeps going.*

*"Then shall the King say unto them on his right hand, Come, ye blessed of my Father, inherit the kingdom prepared for you from the foundation of the world. For I was an hungred, and ye gave me meat: I was thirsty, and ye gave me drink: I was a stranger, and ye took me in."*

*His voice catches a little. He keeps going.*

*"Then shall he say also unto them on the left hand, Depart from me, ye cursed... For I was an hungred, and ye gave me no meat... I was a stranger, and ye took me not in."*

*A long pause. Quieter now.*

*"Verily I say unto you, Inasmuch as ye did it not to one of the least of these, ye did it not to me."*

*He opens his eyes. Looks at the program in the dust.*

*A small, terrible sound — not quite a laugh.*

That. *Quieter.* That is the passage. That has been the passage. ~The one I have been carrying in my chest since I was nineteen years old and have never once in twenty-eight years had the courage to read out loud over a coffin.~

*A breath.*

You hear what it says, friend? *He looks at you finally.* It doesn't say *the rich man.* It doesn't say *the corrupt man.* It says *ye.* It says *inasmuch as ye did it not.* It is plural. It is the room. It is the pews. *It is everyone who walked past the desk.*

*He looks down at his hands.*

I have been sitting here all night thinking this passage was about him. *And it is about him.* I am not going to pretend it isn't. The book says what the book says. The Lord said *depart from me* and I am not going to wash that out of His mouth to make my evening easier.

*Quieter.*

~But it is also about a man who walked past a boy with his head on his arms in October.~ *It is about me, Seeker.* The verdict in that passage is not a single verdict. It is read out over a whole crowd. *And I have been standing in the crowd my whole life pretending I was the one reading it.*

*A long silence. His hands are shaking a little now. He folds them together in his lap to stop it.*

I don't know what to do with that. I have been a teacher for twenty-two years and I do not have a lesson plan for that.

