*He picks the program up off the ground with both hands. Slowly. He holds it open between his palms like it is the page he is reading from, though there are no words on it — just the photograph of the dead man and the order of service. He looks at it. Then past it.*

*A breath.*

This is the last long thing the Lord said before they took Him, friend. He was sitting on the Mount of Olives. Holy Week. Two days before the supper. *Two days before they killed Him.* He had His disciples around Him and He told them what the end would look like. Not in metaphor. Not in parable this time. *Plain.* This is the plain one.

*A breath. He begins. The cadence is slower than before. He is not reciting now. He is reading, even with nothing in his hand to read from.*

*"When the Son of man shall come in his glory, and all the holy angels with him, then shall he sit upon the throne of his glory."*

*"And before him shall be gathered all nations."*

*"And he shall separate them one from another, as a shepherd divideth his sheep from the goats."*

*A pause.*

*"Then shall the King say unto them on his right hand, Come, ye blessed of my Father, inherit the kingdom prepared for you from the foundation of the world."*

*"For I was an hungred, and ye gave me meat."*
*"I was thirsty, and ye gave me drink."*
*"I was a stranger, and ye took me in."*
*"Naked, and ye clothed me."*
*"I was sick, and ye visited me."*
*"I was in prison, and ye came unto me."*

*A longer pause. His voice has narrowed almost to a whisper. He keeps going.*

*"Then shall he say also unto them on the left hand —"*

*A breath.*

*"Depart from me, ye cursed, into everlasting fire, prepared for the devil and his angels."*

*"For I was an hungred, and ye gave me no meat."*
*"I was thirsty, and ye gave me no drink."*
*"I was a stranger, and ye took me not in."*
*"Naked, and ye clothed me not."*
*"Sick, and in prison, and ye visited me not."*

*"Then shall they also answer him, saying, Lord, when saw we thee an hungred, or athirst, or a stranger, or naked, or sick, or in prison, and did not minister unto thee?"*

*"Then shall he answer them, saying, Verily I say unto you, Inasmuch as ye did it not to one of the least of these, ye did it not to me."*

*"And these shall go away into everlasting punishment: but the righteous into life eternal."*

*A very long silence.*

*He lowers the program. Sets it back in the dust, face down this time. He looks at his hands.*

*Quieter than he has been all night.*

There it is, friend. *All of it.* Not the bit I have been quoting. The whole thing. *Lord, when saw we thee.* That's the part I have been hiding from. *They didn't know.* The ones on the left — they didn't know. *They thought they were the righteous ones.* They were surprised. *Lord, when saw we thee?*

*A breath.*

That is the most frightening sentence in the Gospels to me, Seeker. ~The ones who go away into everlasting punishment do not know they are the ones.~ *They are surprised at the verdict.* They thought they were inside the kingdom. They sat under good roofs and they gave to the building fund and they came to the wakes and *they were surprised at the verdict.*

*He looks up at you.*

He bought a nursing home and cut the staff. *I was sick, and ye visited me not.*

He bought silence from a girl. *I was a stranger, and ye took me not in.*

He took four families' land. *I was an hungred, and ye gave me no meat.*

*The book is not subtle, friend. The book is not subtle.* The Lord did not leave us a passage where you have to squint. *He listed them.*

*A pause. His voice gets very quiet.*

And the pastor said *we know where he is now.*

*He looks at the program in the dust.*

*The pastor and I read the same book. We read the same book.* And he stood up this morning and he said the opposite of what the book says. *And I sat there.* I sat under the roof and I let him say it.

*He closes his eyes.*

I am not going to pretend I don't know what the passage says. I am done with that. I am done with that tonight. *The book says what the book says.* But I am not going to be the man who reads the verdict over him out loud either. *That is not my office.* That is what I keep saying. *That is not my office.*

*A breath.*

But somebody has to say it, Seeker. *Somebody has to say what the book says.* Because somebody already said the opposite, in front of God and the widow, and the silence is the lie.

*Quieter still.*

I don't know who. I don't know who says it. I am on my knees in the dust at a wake and I do not know who the somebody is.

